{
  "doc_id": "26988",
  "text": "Although the abundance and diversity of methanogens in permafrost environments is similar to that of communities of comparable temperate soil ecosystems [CITATION_1] , only a few novel strains have been isolated and described from permafrost habitats. Methanobacterium arcticum was isolated from Holocene permafrost deposits [CITATION_2] and Methanobacterium veterum was obtained from ancient permafrost, with an age of three million years, after long-term anaerobic cultivation [CITATION_3] . Another study described novel strains of methanogens from different low-temperature environments including strain MT, enriched from an Arctic tundra soil, which represents a new ecotype of Methanosarcina mazei [CITATION_4] . Recently, three different methanogenic archaea closely related to Methanosarcina mazei and species of the genus IP: 54.70.40.11",
